  "rendered": {
    "title": "Steadier chat streams and a survivable Windows updater",
    "intro": "Today's nightly tightens the seams where chat meets persistence and where Windows desktop hands off to its own installer. Streaming replies stop blinking when history catches up, stalled remote sessions surface real errors instead of a frozen \"connecting\" state, and the Windows updater now leaves a paper trail and reliably relaunches Aura after install.",
    "entries": [
      {
        "batch_id": "entry-1",
        "time_label": "2:37 PM",
        "started_at": "2026-05-02T21:37:08.000Z",
        "ended_at": "2026-05-02T21:40:29.000Z",
        "title": "Org identity for remote chat and a debuggable Windows updater handoff",
        "summary": "Two reliability fixes landed back to back: remote harness sessions now carry the right org header, and the Windows updater stops disappearing silently after install.",
        "items": [
          {
            "text": "Remote harness chat sessions now populate the X-Aura-Org-Id context from the project when agent metadata is incomplete, so server-side requests no longer drop their org identity.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "9bbe1ae4500f19f6a7e2f9fc278293b40c372761"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          },
          {
            "text": "On Windows, the NSIS installer handoff now writes a per-version log and the desktop app retries its single-instance acquisition during an update relaunch, so updates that previously quit without diagnostics now leave evidence and come back up cleanly.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "b7d61680e560cbca7b1df6f3ec16c783705f7fff"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "batch_id": "entry-2",
        "time_label": "2:55 PM",
        "started_at": "2026-05-02T21:55:05.000Z",
        "ended_at": "2026-05-02T21:55:05.000Z",
        "title": "Remote chat surfaces stalls instead of hanging on \"connecting\"",
        "summary": "Swarm session startup and the WebSocket bridge now treat silence and bad frames as real errors, so the UI can stop showing an indefinite connecting state.",
        "items": [
          {
            "text": "Swarm session startup waits for an explicit session_ready signal and a new turn watchdog broadcasts a synthetic terminal error if the remote runtime emits no events within 30s or runs past the 5-minute turn cap.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "33ad453f9e8aa1af16d78e0837800f09d16bec15"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          },
          {
            "text": "The WebSocket bridge now rejects unsupported frame types as terminal errors instead of letting the SSE keep-alive mask a dead stream, so chat fails fast with a real message.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "33ad453f9e8aa1af16d78e0837800f09d16bec15"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "batch_id": "entry-3",
        "time_label": "2:56 PM",
        "started_at": "2026-05-02T21:56:36.000Z",
        "ended_at": "2026-05-02T21:56:36.000Z",
        "title": "Updater installs move off the Tokio runtime thread",
        "summary": "The Windows install path is reworked so it doesn't deadlock the desktop event loop, and the local smoke script can verify NSIS builds.",
        "items": [
          {
            "text": "User-approved installs now run on a named OS thread, so the tao event loop no longer needs a Tokio reactor to drive the updater handoff.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "9e665002e20c855d8954d65ed69b7823b7b8af45"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          },
          {
            "text": "The desktop auto-update smoke script falls back to NSIS DisplayVersion when PE metadata is empty, keeping local Windows release verification working end to end.",
            "commit_shas": [
              "9e665002e20c855d8954d65ed69b7823b7b8af45"
            ],
            "confidence": "high"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
